PLEASE READ ALL THE WAY THROUGH: Wreckers! It‚Äôs that time of year again, but we‚Äôre required to celebrate a bit differently this time around.

Due to COVID, we will be transitioning from a bonfire to an outdoor movie night to celebrate our school and community. There is a 250 person max, face mask and/or shield must be worn, and a free ticket must be ‚Äúpurchased‚Äù in advance to reserve your seat. IT IS LIMITED TO HS STUDENTS ONLY PLUS 1 GUEST DUE TO COVID-19 REQUIREMENTS AND REGULATIONS. (This guest can be of any age with a ticket). So again, high school student plus 1 guest.

The cheer team will be selling candy and beverages, L&L is supplying the food and we will be playing to back-to-back spooky movie features to spend some quality time as a community, six feet apart. Homecoming court will be recognized and king and queen crowned at 8PM. Bring a blanket or chairs to sit on! Again, IT IS FREE, but YOU MUST RESERVE YOUR SPOT AHEAD OF TIME, otherwise you will be turned away at the door.

Our main priority is everyone‚Äôs safety and of course fun. We hope to see you all there! üß°üñ§

WHS Class Of 2021
July 24 at 10:37 AM ¬∑

After a lot of planning, postponing, rescheduling, replanning, and stress the 2020 Prom finally happened...and it was worth the wait! We‚Äôd like to thank Mr. DeSpirito for his support and advice and the many exchanged messages throughout the summer, Mr. Hearne for helping with paperwork, all calls, and chaperoning, and Dr. Nelson, Mrs. Moucheron, and Connie Derr for agreeing to chaperone and enduring the heat with us. Also, Mrs. Cabe who would‚Äôve been there if we didn‚Äôt have to reschedule. Most of all we thank the prom committee for all the work they‚Äôve been doing since January; Lilli Kunkle, Kelly Elizabeth Royer, Maddie Hinkle, Ashley James, Alyssa Heister, Antonia Prete, Shayla Heitczman, and Isabella Wagner. While it may not have looked like we envisioned, it was still beautiful. And finally THANK YOU to the students and parents for your flexibility and understanding.

6. The CDC recommends that everyone wear a mask upon entering and exiting the establishment as well as when walking through to visit the restroom, however this is a RECOMMENDATION not a law so you will not be denied access if you don‚Äôt have a mask.

Today was the first day for distributing food for the summer and we had 76 families come for food. A big thank you to the following volunteers who are willing to donate their time over the summer to help with this:

Heather Katchur, Erin and Paul Digennaro, John McGee, Brian Lutz, Autumn Gilbert, Becky McFadden, Theresa D'Andrea, Georgeann Herling, Georgia Farrow, Donna Thomas, Betty Henry, Carol Eroh, Karen Andrew, Kelly Royer, Isabella Wagner, Madilyn Hinkle, Lilli Kunkle, Ashley James and Alyssa Heister.

Without them, willing to volunteer their time, this program would not be possible. Thank you for making a difference for all the Weatherly families!

Food is available for pick up every Monday and Thursday from 11 am to 12 pm at the parent pick up area located behind the Elementary/Middle School.

Thank you,
Terry

post_text:
On behalf of all teachers and staff of the WASD....

We wanted to take a minute and thank the community and parents. Please know that each and every one of you is appreciated and we are grateful for you and your efforts. You helped make this crazy time during a pandemic of transitioning from school days between walls, chalkboards, friends, and cooperative play/learning to online learning in front of a computer screen all day with hardly any social interaction a success. At first, it may have seemed to be a tough thing to accomplish, but we ALL did it TOGETHER. We are so thankful for your help, flexibility, understanding, patience, & love of your child(s)/children(s) success and efforts in their education!

REMEMBER...TOGETHER WE ALL CAN ACHIEVE AMAZING THINGS.... WE ARE THE WRECKERS!üß°üñ§

Also, CONGRATULATIONS and GOOD LUCK to the CLASS of 2020!!

Love,
WASD TEACHERS AND STAFF

Gov. Wolf, Treasurer Torsella Announce Property Tax/Rent Rebates Arriving Early to Help Seniors, Others During COVID-19 Pandemic

About the Property Tax/Rent Rebate Program
The rebate program benefits eligible Pennsylvanians age 65 and older; widows and widowers age 50 and older; and people with disabilities age 18 and older. The income limit is $35,000 a year for homeowners and $15,000 annually for renters, and half of Social Security income is excluded. It is free to apply for a rebate.

The maximum standard rebate is $650, but supplemental rebates for certain qualifying homeowners can boost rebates to $975.

All seniors who ordered a cap and gown may pick them up on Monday, April 27th. Follow the subsequent schedule and please do not get out of your cars. The cap and gowns will be brought to your vehicle.

Seniors with the last name beginning with A to G may report to the high school office between 9 am and 10 am.

Seniors with the last name beginning with H to L may report to the high school office between 10 am and 11 am.

Seniors with the last name beginning with M to Z may report to the high school office between 11 am and 12 pm.

Also, any senior who ordered announcements will be given them at this time.

Details of graduation will be forthcoming in the near future.

Dear Class of 2020,
We want you to know how sorry we are that the last months of your senior year are filled with such uncertainty. Monday we were going to start selling tickets for the prom, but unfortunately like everything else, we need to hold off for now. We want you to know though, that this does not mean prom is cancelled. Like so many other things in our lives right now, it must be put on hold. We promise that we will do everything in our power to make sure that you are not deprived of your senior prom. When this threat is over we‚Äôll celebrate and ‚ÄúParty like it‚Äôs 1920!‚Äù
Sincerely,
Class of 2021

post_text: Attention all parents and students in grades K through 5. The Weatherly Area School District plans to move to on-line instruction beginning March 30th. We are asking that you please come to the school tomorrow between the hours of 9 am and 11 am to allow your child to pick up textbooks. The district is also offering devices at this time that will be allowed to be used until school is back in session or the end of the school year. A parent or guardian must be present to pick up the device and sign a waiver. Families that do not have internet access at home will be provided a mobile hot spot. These hot spots are not available today so these families will be notified when to come to the school and pick them up. Please make every attempt possible to come to the school in the designated time tomorrow between 9 am and 11 am. Teachers will be working with students all next week to make sure that every student is able to access the on-line platform needed for future instruction. Thank you for your cooperation.

PA Governor, Tom Wolf, has announced the closure of all K-12 schools for the commonwealth beginning on Monday, March 16th. This closure is currently scheduled for 10 business days. WASD will continue to monitor the situation and share information as soon as it becomes available.

On Monday, March 16th the building will be open (9-11am) to the public so anyone can retrieve school materials or personal items. Over the next 10 days students are not responsible for online instructional material. We will continue to work diligently to keep the public informed and our students safe.

Congratulations to our December Senior of the Month~Lexi Berger!

Lexi Berger, daughter of Jennifer and Terry Berger, Weatherly, has been named Senior of the Month for December at Weatherly Area High School.

Lexi serves as President of Weatherly‚Äôs chapter of the National Honor Society. She is the Vice President of SGA, and Vice President of the Class of 2020. Lexi is a member of the varsity soccer and track teams, and was manager of the boys‚Äô soccer team for two years, as well as a member of Weatherly‚Äôs cheerleading squad. Her cheerleading awards include the ‚ÄúGood Deed‚Äù Award, the ‚ÄúPay it Forward‚Äù Award, and the Varsity Cheer Fellowship Award.

In the community, Lexi volunteered with the Saint de Paul‚Äôs Soup Kitchen as a kitchen worker. She is employed as a server at Heritage Hill in Weatherly, and as a busser and waitress at Jack‚Äôs Grille in White Haven.

Sponsor for the month of December is David Feaster Excavating in Weatherly.

HS FCS classes
Just Because poem

Stereotyping can hurt people of all nations, color, size, gender, age, and race. This year the HS FCS classes each created a class poem called Just Because. The poem is personal in nature and helps to fight against stereotyping. You will notice this poem posted throughout the school. The class invites you to read our words. We want everybody to know we are all unique in our own way and that is OKAY! Don‚Äôt judge people because they are different, CELEBRATE IT! STOP THE HATE!

post_text: Mr. Moran's AP US History got a hands-on history lesson about the American Industrial Revolution. They toured the Anthracite Mining Museum in Scranton recently and were given a personal tour by a Polish Immigrant who worked as a breaker boy in Scranton for several years and was a wealth of knowledge for the students. They even got a local history lesson about the Buck Mountain Coal Company and its connection to the American Civil War.

Congratulations to the Lady Wreckers on their first win!

Weatherly-Meadowbrook Christian
Ashley James exploded for 25 points to lead Weatherly to a 40-29 non-league victory over Meadowbrook Christian.
James did her damage early and late, scoring 12 first quarter points and 11 fourth quarter points for the Wreckers (1-0).

WEATHERLY
Kane 0-0-0-0, Kislan 1-0-2-2, James 7-11-15-25, Miller 4-0-0-8, Cichon 0-0-2-0, Lowman 1-0-1-2, Von Frisch 0-0-0-0, Chincola 1-1-2-3. TOTALS: 14-12-22-40.

Stokes 5-4-6-14, Canelo 0-0-0-0, Hartman 1-0-2-2, Toland 1-0-0-2, Devlin 1-2-4-4, Baney 3-1-1-7, McNeal 0-0-2-0. TOTALS: 11-7-15-29.
